48
00:02:00,599 --> 00:02:02,442
We know, or we're learning, that game development

49
00:02:02,482 --> 00:02:03,684
is really, really, really hard.

50
00:02:04,004 --> 00:02:05,326
One of the hardest things about it

51
00:02:06,027 --> 00:02:06,729
is communication.

52
00:02:08,845 --> 00:02:13,406
Now, I like to learn, I read books, I find material on communication so I can improve

53
00:02:13,906 --> 00:02:17,507
my skills in communication with the teams that I work with and the people that I interact

54
00:02:17,527 --> 00:02:17,647
with.

55
00:02:18,007 --> 00:02:20,848
I do that all the time, and hopefully you're doing that all the time also.

56
00:02:21,708 --> 00:02:26,529
One of the books that has held up for a long time for me, and he's written more material

57
00:02:26,569 --> 00:02:32,771
than this on things having to do with trust and truths, is this one, Seven Habits of Highly

58
00:02:32,791 --> 00:02:33,471
Effective People.

59
00:02:34,871 --> 00:02:37,273
In it, one of those habits that he points out is communication.

60
00:02:37,593 --> 00:02:39,895
Seek first to understand, then be understood.

61
00:02:42,317 --> 00:02:44,939
And he makes the point that our whole lives...

62
00:02:46,132 --> 00:02:49,295
We're spending time speaking and writing,

63
00:02:49,395 --> 00:02:51,037
and in our classes in school,

64
00:02:51,097 --> 00:02:52,879
we learn how to communicate outward.

65
00:02:53,239 --> 00:02:54,140
We're broadcasting.

66
00:02:54,160 --> 00:02:56,663
We learn a lot about broadcasting messages,

67
00:02:56,703 --> 00:02:57,684
things that we care about,

68
00:02:57,724 --> 00:02:59,426
because we assume a lot of people care about

69
00:02:59,886 --> 00:03:00,667
what we care about,

70
00:03:00,707 --> 00:03:02,128
so we want to tell them all about it.

71
00:03:02,368 --> 00:03:03,930
But we don't spend a lot of time listening.

72
00:03:04,230 --> 00:03:05,872
And most of what we do as producers,

73
00:03:05,932 --> 00:03:07,273
or what we should be doing as producers,

74
00:03:07,333 --> 00:03:08,835
is listening and observing

75
00:03:08,875 --> 00:03:10,296
and gaining situational awareness.

76
00:03:11,387 --> 00:03:15,129
really cluing in to what's happening with our projects and our teams and

77
00:03:15,690 --> 00:03:18,111
if you're on the development side with the publisher and vice versa

78
00:03:19,052 --> 00:03:19,753
if you're a publisher.

79
00:03:20,773 --> 00:03:23,675
We don't spend nearly enough time really synthesizing the information that's

80
00:03:23,715 --> 00:03:24,316
coming to us.

81
00:03:25,216 --> 00:03:27,118
So we really have to develop our skills in listening.

82
00:03:28,098 --> 00:03:28,899
And it's a practice.

83
00:03:32,052 --> 00:03:34,353
So since this is sort of an overview of communication,

84
00:03:34,393 --> 00:03:36,833
I'll just cover a couple of basic topics,

85
00:03:36,993 --> 00:03:39,454
things that you've probably heard many times in school,

86
00:03:39,514 --> 00:03:41,334
but it doesn't hurt to refresh our memory.

87
00:03:42,054 --> 00:03:44,155
Here are some things that are barriers to communication,

88
00:03:44,175 --> 00:03:45,875
just generally, just broadly.

89
00:03:46,235 --> 00:03:47,576
These are broad principles,

90
00:03:48,696 --> 00:03:52,457
things that can impede good communication between people.

91
00:03:54,637 --> 00:03:55,898
So physical barriers.

92
00:03:57,752 --> 00:04:01,174
Nowadays, it's not uncommon at all to work with

93
00:04:01,214 --> 00:04:03,115
teams who are on the other side of the world.

94
00:04:06,116 --> 00:04:08,978
Very often, we work in buildings where we may

95
00:04:09,038 --> 00:04:11,399
not see other people who are in the building

96
00:04:11,439 --> 00:04:15,061
with us for days, weeks, months. I was talking

97
00:04:15,122 --> 00:04:17,583
to one of our producers last night who said

98
00:04:17,923 --> 00:04:19,284
he got to meet one of our animators

99
00:04:19,304 --> 00:04:20,565
for the first time. He said, how long have

100
00:04:20,605 --> 00:04:22,166
you been here? He assumed it was maybe a

101
00:04:22,206 --> 00:04:23,606
month or two. Two years.

102
00:04:25,187 --> 00:04:27,148
So, it's funny how long...

103
00:04:28,100 --> 00:04:31,103
time can go by for that we don't interact with others who

104
00:04:31,423 --> 00:04:33,225
are actually working on the same project with us,

105
00:04:33,665 --> 00:04:34,846
or on other projects near us.

106
00:04:37,048 --> 00:04:38,269
Choice of the wrong medium.

107
00:04:38,829 --> 00:04:40,010
We do this all the time.

108
00:04:40,451 --> 00:04:40,971
What's one of the,

109
00:04:41,511 --> 00:04:43,553
what's one of those mediums that we use all the time

110
00:04:43,593 --> 00:04:45,755
where we probably should have chosen some other medium?

111
00:04:47,316 --> 00:04:47,476
Hmm?

112
00:04:48,677 --> 00:04:49,578
Email, for sure.

113
00:04:50,159 --> 00:04:52,220
That's a, that's like low-hanging fruit, right?

114
00:04:52,581 --> 00:04:55,443
All the time we use email for things that we shouldn't be using email for.

115
00:04:56,254 --> 00:04:58,215
Semantic barriers are language.

116
00:04:58,655 --> 00:05:01,237
We use a word that somebody else takes an exception to.

117
00:05:02,317 --> 00:05:05,239
That sort of stops their, the flow of communication,

118
00:05:05,279 --> 00:05:05,839
they're listening.

119
00:05:07,020 --> 00:05:08,201
Might stop you from talking.

120
00:05:08,341 --> 00:05:10,542
Cultural barriers, some of these are pretty obvious,

121
00:05:10,562 --> 00:05:11,983
I won't go too deep into these,

122
00:05:12,023 --> 00:05:13,544
just, it's good to be aware of these things.

123
00:05:14,144 --> 00:05:17,566
Psychological barriers is one of the biggest ones, actually,

124
00:05:17,626 --> 00:05:19,827
because you can only ever control...

125
00:05:20,729 --> 00:05:23,990
yourself, the communication that you're providing and the listening that you're doing,

126
00:05:24,290 --> 00:05:26,371
you can never control anyone else, right?

127
00:05:26,791 --> 00:05:31,312
So, psychological and attitudinal barriers, while they might frustrate us,

128
00:05:32,032 --> 00:05:34,833
they might be things that we're aware we have to pay attention to,

129
00:05:36,353 --> 00:05:38,313
it's one of those things that makes communication hard,

130
00:05:38,453 --> 00:05:41,394
because we can't force the other person to really hear our message.

131
00:05:42,374 --> 00:05:45,455
All we can do is a better job on our end of conveying it

132
00:05:45,915 --> 00:05:48,216
and being aware if they're getting it or not.

133
00:05:49,809 --> 00:05:51,450
in varying perceptions of reality,

134
00:05:52,571 --> 00:05:54,933
which are caused by levels of understanding and comprehension.

135
00:05:54,953 --> 00:05:56,974
So everybody has a different view, a different filter

136
00:05:57,415 --> 00:06:00,377
that they use to see the world and to see projects.

137
00:06:00,817 --> 00:06:02,719
And some people might think game development's easy

138
00:06:02,819 --> 00:06:04,820
or should be easy, and some people think it's hard.

139
00:06:05,381 --> 00:06:07,302
And it should be hard if you want to do a good job.

140
00:06:08,043 --> 00:06:09,824
There's a lot of different ideas

141
00:06:10,665 --> 00:06:13,327
of what game development is and what it's not.

142
00:06:14,147 --> 00:06:15,248
Nobody shares one.

143
00:06:15,948 --> 00:06:17,550
People don't share one idea of that.

144
00:06:17,937 --> 00:06:19,738
It's important to know where the other person's coming from.

145
00:06:24,040 --> 00:06:26,201
And it's really easy for us just to assume it's the other person.

146
00:06:27,001 --> 00:06:27,902
We have to get through that.

147
00:06:29,483 --> 00:06:30,483
And it comes up all the time.

148
00:06:31,223 --> 00:06:34,205
And at Gearbox, with the people that we work with,

149
00:06:34,285 --> 00:06:36,306
our partners inside the company,

150
00:06:36,326 --> 00:06:38,627
you always have to kind of just pause for a second.

151
00:06:39,948 --> 00:06:42,109
And think about, is this quality issue

152
00:06:42,149 --> 00:06:43,530
something that this person...

153
00:06:44,579 --> 00:06:45,941
You know, did they do this on purpose?

154
00:06:46,301 --> 00:06:47,623
Was it a timing issue?

155
00:06:49,205 --> 00:06:50,947
Am I saying something where

156
00:06:51,628 --> 00:06:53,830
they already have built up a wall to it

157
00:06:54,251 --> 00:06:55,432
and I wasn't aware of that?

158
00:06:55,793 --> 00:06:56,534
What's going on there?

159
00:06:56,854 --> 00:06:58,997
And you must encounter these things all the time,

160
00:06:59,177 --> 00:07:00,438
I would guess, if you're making games.

161
00:07:02,501 --> 00:07:04,383
So, the description of the talk...

162
00:07:05,732 --> 00:07:08,772
is about communication being the bane of all postmortems.

163
00:07:09,212 --> 00:07:11,353
Well, I'm, I'm really sad that Game Developer Magazine's

164
00:07:11,373 --> 00:07:13,053
not still published in the way it used to be,

165
00:07:13,113 --> 00:07:15,634
although we still see great articles on Gamasutra.

166
00:07:17,674 --> 00:07:20,595
But one of the articles that, as producers,

167
00:07:22,215 --> 00:07:25,596
we always enjoyed looking for were these postmortems.

168
00:07:26,536 --> 00:07:29,877
And the reason I say communication's the bane

169
00:07:30,517 --> 00:07:32,718
of all postmortems is because you just waited for it.

170
00:07:33,489 --> 00:07:37,051
You waited for that team, the person who's writing that article,

171
00:07:37,411 --> 00:07:40,533
that postmortem, to say communication was one of the top problems.

172
00:07:40,913 --> 00:07:42,894
Every time. And if they didn't, you called them a liar.

173
00:07:46,456 --> 00:07:48,177
Especially because you were probably having those problems.

174
00:07:48,918 --> 00:07:49,138
Well,

175
00:07:52,560 --> 00:07:54,641
in this particular issue, which was

176
00:07:55,922 --> 00:07:57,202
at the beginning of 09, I think,

177
00:07:59,104 --> 00:07:59,884
Brandon Sheffield.

178
00:08:01,231 --> 00:08:03,452
wrote up just a quick recap of some things

179
00:08:04,352 --> 00:08:07,213
that he'd run into, or he'd come across in postmortems.

180
00:08:08,573 --> 00:08:10,013
And it kind of sets the tone, I think,

181
00:08:10,053 --> 00:08:11,554
just that over and over again,

182
00:08:13,174 --> 00:08:14,595
we come across these same issues.

183
00:08:15,935 --> 00:08:18,176
So Penny Arcade.

184
00:08:19,496 --> 00:08:22,037
They simply fail to employ best practices,

185
00:08:22,117 --> 00:08:24,097
which are things that you agree in communication

186
00:08:24,137 --> 00:08:24,837
amongst each other,

187
00:08:25,798 --> 00:08:26,998
are things that you should be doing

188
00:08:27,078 --> 00:08:28,298
so that you don't have to have

189
00:08:29,230 --> 00:08:32,592
more formal rules. They're, they're guidelines for you to

190
00:08:32,652 --> 00:08:35,274
follow. And you set these in agreement with the

191
00:08:35,314 --> 00:08:37,896
team, because these are the things that are gonna

192
00:08:37,996 --> 00:08:39,537
keep your project from going off the rails.

193
00:08:40,857 --> 00:08:43,719
They, they knew better. They simply failed to employ

194
00:08:43,759 --> 00:08:45,460
best practices. How often does it happen? I know

195
00:08:45,480 --> 00:08:51,924
it happens pretty often. Happens at Gearbox. I know

196
00:08:51,964 --> 00:08:54,946
from developer friends I've talked to, it happens throughout

197
00:08:54,966 --> 00:08:56,106
the industry. We just forget.

198
00:08:58,691 --> 00:08:59,371
At Harmonix.

199
00:09:00,772 --> 00:09:01,593
On Guitar Hero.

200
00:09:02,874 --> 00:09:03,134
Well...

201
00:09:05,776 --> 00:09:07,157
they created an early schedule.

202
00:09:07,577 --> 00:09:09,639
They had a communication plan for how they would go

203
00:09:09,699 --> 00:09:10,660
about making the game.

204
00:09:12,141 --> 00:09:12,901
And then what happened?

205
00:09:13,642 --> 00:09:16,984
As things went along, they forgot to keep up-to-date

206
00:09:17,044 --> 00:09:18,585
with specification of what they were doing.

207
00:09:19,546 --> 00:09:23,168
So if you're aware of the PMBOK,

208
00:09:23,249 --> 00:09:26,171
or the Project Management Institute's guide

209
00:09:26,231 --> 00:09:27,391
on how to do project management...

210
00:09:28,796 --> 00:09:31,477
PMI tends to avoid talking about Agile development.

211
00:09:31,497 --> 00:09:34,299
At least, I don't see PMI talking a lot about Agile.

212
00:09:34,519 --> 00:09:37,181
They use other language to talk about

213
00:09:37,541 --> 00:09:41,043
more traditional approaches to project management,

214
00:09:41,423 --> 00:09:43,905
which still fit within an Agile structure.

215
00:09:45,085 --> 00:09:46,626
One of those, they talk about a rolling wave.

216
00:09:47,544 --> 00:09:48,765
And that's a common theme.

217
00:09:49,005 --> 00:09:50,425
And in communication as a producer,

218
00:09:50,465 --> 00:09:54,687
you have to be ready to catch the project as it moves along,

219
00:09:54,847 --> 00:09:57,668
the idea of the sort of rolling wave in development,

220
00:09:58,148 --> 00:10:00,629
to stay on top of the wave and to continue

221
00:10:00,709 --> 00:10:04,670
to bring ideas and specifications back

222
00:10:04,730 --> 00:10:06,851
into the project so that it can be tasked properly

223
00:10:07,131 --> 00:10:07,971
and be broken down.

224
00:10:08,031 --> 00:10:09,612
If you're running an agile project,

225
00:10:09,932 --> 00:10:12,533
then you're breaking down epic stories into smaller stories.

226
00:10:12,853 --> 00:10:15,153
The smaller that you get in the story, the better spec,

227
00:10:15,193 --> 00:10:16,514
the better it can be estimated.

228
00:10:17,758 --> 00:10:18,998
They just sort of forgot to do that.

229
00:10:22,639 --> 00:10:27,280
Max Hoberman, great developer, developed multiplayer for Halo.

230
00:10:28,640 --> 00:10:30,641
Went off and made his own studio, Certain Affinity.

231
00:10:30,681 --> 00:10:34,221
He was used to open pit environments, open communication.

232
00:10:34,661 --> 00:10:35,682
Had a passion project.

233
00:10:35,742 --> 00:10:37,362
Age of Booty was their original IP.

234
00:10:38,582 --> 00:10:42,663
Even in that environment, they forgot that their teams

235
00:10:42,703 --> 00:10:44,103
had to communicate with each other.

236
00:10:44,524 --> 00:10:46,704
They didn't have a formal tasking plan.

237
00:10:47,430 --> 00:10:50,475
for how they would ensure that dependencies worked out

238
00:10:50,976 --> 00:10:51,858
between those teams.

239
00:10:53,360 --> 00:10:55,203
It ended up costing them a lot of time and money.

240
00:10:57,206 --> 00:10:59,971
And I won't, I won't go on and on on each of these for now.

241
00:11:02,713 --> 00:11:05,114
But Brandon says, a lot of these issues have to do

242
00:11:05,134 --> 00:11:06,394
with scheduling and communication,

243
00:11:06,434 --> 00:11:09,136
which in turn has to do with the quality of producers.

244
00:11:09,836 --> 00:11:11,917
And I'm really heartened to see you all here

245
00:11:11,977 --> 00:11:14,258
because I know you want to be quality producers.

246
00:11:15,718 --> 00:11:17,179
Not everyone can be here right now.

247
00:11:17,239 --> 00:11:19,260
It just shows your interest, though,

248
00:11:19,500 --> 00:11:20,480
in furthering your careers.

249
00:11:22,461 --> 00:11:25,363
And these have to be things that we remind ourselves of

250
00:11:25,403 --> 00:11:27,403
all the time, to be quality producers.

251
00:11:29,945 --> 00:11:31,005
But we just run into these.

252
00:11:31,085 --> 00:11:31,585
Thanks, Brandon.

253
00:11:32,824 --> 00:11:34,004
in postmortems all the time.

254
00:11:34,924 --> 00:11:36,624
So what are the kinds of things that we can do

255
00:11:36,704 --> 00:11:38,605
to make sure that we're learning from these mistakes?

256
00:11:40,205 --> 00:11:42,666
And how do we use communication

257
00:11:43,686 --> 00:11:46,387
to reinforce with the team that we have learned something

258
00:11:47,447 --> 00:11:48,847
and that we're going to get better?

259
00:11:50,288 --> 00:11:51,348
And that it won't happen again.

260
00:11:52,548 --> 00:11:53,709
Well, sprint retrospectives.

261
00:11:53,889 --> 00:11:56,209
How many of you here are employing an agile methodology

262
00:11:56,229 --> 00:11:57,770
in your studio or in your development environment?

263
00:11:59,375 --> 00:12:05,419
many of you. How many of you are not? Specifically not? Okay. So for those of you who, one or

264
00:12:05,459 --> 00:12:08,921
two, but for the most part, for those of you who didn't raise your hand, either you're

265
00:12:08,941 --> 00:12:14,224
not sure or you're looking to get into development, you've heard maybe a lot about Agile and you've

266
00:12:14,244 --> 00:12:19,268
heard about other methodologies. Sprint retrospectives are a great way to make sure that you're actually

267
00:12:19,308 --> 00:12:24,291
absorbing these best practices and that you are culturally building up, up

268
00:12:24,744 --> 00:12:28,166
a good way of talking to each other on your teams

269
00:12:28,527 --> 00:12:33,930
so that you avoid wasting effort and having angry developers around you.

270
00:12:34,470 --> 00:12:36,712
And in those sprint retrospectives, you have to talk about

271
00:12:37,232 --> 00:12:40,094
things that you need to start doing, things that you need to stop doing,

272
00:12:40,594 --> 00:12:44,657
and things that are going pretty good, continue, will observe, good so far.

273
00:12:45,597 --> 00:12:47,158
That's a really useful team discussion.

274
00:12:48,359 --> 00:12:50,140
Now there's also a thing called an AAR.

275
00:12:50,180 --> 00:12:52,321
This comes from military training.

276
00:12:54,125 --> 00:12:56,033
We use it, some people call it a mid-mortem.

277
00:12:56,836 --> 00:12:58,623
It's really similar to a mid-mortem.

278
00:12:58,924 --> 00:13:00,049
Okay.

279
00:13:01,192 --> 00:13:04,495
Difference here, though, is where a sprint retrospective

280
00:13:04,575 --> 00:13:06,316
tends to be, at least in my experience,

281
00:13:06,356 --> 00:13:09,099
I'm sure many of you probably have different experiences,

282
00:13:09,179 --> 00:13:11,260
but my experience usually is a big discussion.

283
00:13:12,201 --> 00:13:13,923
And if you as the producer are there,

284
00:13:14,303 --> 00:13:16,184
you may be sort of guiding people through it

285
00:13:16,224 --> 00:13:17,325
if you've collected topics,

286
00:13:17,365 --> 00:13:18,867
or guiding your way through those topics.

287
00:13:20,027 --> 00:13:22,229
An AAR tends to be more of a coaching moment

288
00:13:22,810 --> 00:13:23,710
for you as a producer,

289
00:13:24,091 --> 00:13:26,573
or someone who's senior in your organization

290
00:13:27,153 --> 00:13:28,354
to ensure that, in fact...

291
00:13:29,015 --> 00:13:31,178
learning really, this is your moment to say,

292
00:13:32,099 --> 00:13:33,121
have you really got it?

293
00:13:33,401 --> 00:13:35,805
The person who's on your team when you're talking to them

294
00:13:35,865 --> 00:13:37,788
and you can be in a group environment,

295
00:13:37,828 --> 00:13:41,173
you can break up your teams into smaller groups

296
00:13:41,634 --> 00:13:43,096
to really focus that conversation.

297
00:13:43,396 --> 00:13:44,678
But that after action review.

298
00:13:46,609 --> 00:13:49,031
That's about performance in the team context.

299
00:13:49,631 --> 00:13:52,573
How is your performance as a developer,

300
00:13:52,853 --> 00:13:53,794
this is a tool for you to use,

301
00:13:53,834 --> 00:13:55,995
how is your performance as a developer,

302
00:13:56,015 --> 00:13:58,016
how is that with what we were trying

303
00:13:58,036 --> 00:13:59,037
to accomplish on the team?

304
00:13:59,817 --> 00:14:02,179
It's not coaching like performance review coaching.

305
00:14:02,239 --> 00:14:03,140
It's not the kind of thing,

306
00:14:03,160 --> 00:14:05,941
so one of the problems is we don't always coach people

307
00:14:05,961 --> 00:14:06,682
at the right moments.

308
00:14:06,742 --> 00:14:09,003
We wait until they're way off the deep end,

309
00:14:10,044 --> 00:14:11,905
and they've sunk morale of everybody around them,

310
00:14:12,526 --> 00:14:15,848
and we waited until that moment to coach them.

311
00:14:16,700 --> 00:14:19,761
in good behaviors. Don't wait. Do this all the time.

312
00:14:19,901 --> 00:14:22,342
I drop into offices around the studio all the time

313
00:14:23,042 --> 00:14:25,182
to see how things are going, but also I've heard

314
00:14:25,262 --> 00:14:29,203
something about the possibility of a problem, and I just

315
00:14:29,243 --> 00:14:30,063
want to go see what's up.

316
00:14:31,504 --> 00:14:34,945
Or I've heard something where someone's performance is starting

317
00:14:35,085 --> 00:14:38,565
to lag, and I ask that person's lead to go

318
00:14:38,605 --> 00:14:40,126
follow up. Just spend more time with them.

319
00:14:41,546 --> 00:14:43,066
If you guys are familiar with the Hawthorne effect.

320
00:14:44,824 --> 00:14:51,027
There was a social science experiment years ago where in time series studies they wanted

321
00:14:51,087 --> 00:14:54,249
to see if there was a way to have more productivity in factories.

322
00:14:55,370 --> 00:15:04,515
And they set up a test in a factory and they had a survey set up where the scientists would

323
00:15:04,555 --> 00:15:05,575
walk around and ask questions.

324
00:15:05,595 --> 00:15:07,556
It was a survey of people who were working on the floor.

325
00:15:08,655 --> 00:15:14,482
They wanted to see if lighting conditions would change productivity in that factory.

326
00:15:14,862 --> 00:15:16,204
Well, productivity increased.

327
00:15:17,363 --> 00:15:21,346
And at first they believed that the correlation was directly to these new conditions in the factory.

328
00:15:22,127 --> 00:15:25,810
And later they realized that it probably had a lot to do with,

329
00:15:25,870 --> 00:15:29,552
in fact they discovered it did have a lot to do with just that interaction of people,

330
00:15:30,073 --> 00:15:32,295
of those scientists walking around asking questions on the floor.

331
00:15:33,035 --> 00:15:37,259
The Hawthorne effect has to do with changing the outcome of an experiment

332
00:15:37,999 --> 00:15:41,702
simply by holding it and getting involved in the subjects of that experiment.

333
00:15:43,350 --> 00:15:46,793
So we know that interaction with people who are around us

334
00:15:46,853 --> 00:15:48,334
is gonna improve their performance

335
00:15:48,354 --> 00:15:49,294
because they know that you care.

336
00:15:49,714 --> 00:15:52,796
What you have to do is then turn that into data

337
00:15:53,137 --> 00:15:54,538
and turn that into specification,

338
00:15:54,598 --> 00:15:56,419
turn that into things that you're actually tracking

339
00:15:56,699 --> 00:15:57,740
to know the health of your project.

340
00:16:03,423 --> 00:16:05,104
Maintaining best practices is hard.

341
00:16:05,124 --> 00:16:06,725
This is part of why communication's hard.

342
00:16:07,086 --> 00:16:08,567
Maintenance is a hard thing.

343
00:16:08,587 --> 00:16:10,468
You gotta roll up your sleeves, you have to go do it.

344
00:16:12,095 --> 00:16:14,215
It's hard, so a lot of times it just doesn't get done.

345
00:16:15,296 --> 00:16:19,237
But if you want to have a great postmortem and a great AAR,

346
00:16:19,257 --> 00:16:21,017
if you want to be aware of what's happening in your project,

347
00:16:21,297 --> 00:16:23,698
you have to develop situational awareness and keep it.

348
00:16:23,998 --> 00:16:24,858
You can't let it go,

349
00:16:25,099 --> 00:16:27,299
because your project and your team changes all the time.

350
00:16:27,579 --> 00:16:29,720
Dynamics change, your project's changing,

351
00:16:30,020 --> 00:16:30,940
what's the status of it?

352
00:16:31,160 --> 00:16:33,081
Don't just go asking people for status updates.

353
00:16:33,281 --> 00:16:33,921
You have to know.

354
00:16:34,041 --> 00:16:34,781
And if you don't know,

355
00:16:35,121 --> 00:16:36,402
if you don't know, you're not doing your job.

356
00:16:37,382 --> 00:16:38,422
Frequency has to be high,

357
00:16:38,442 --> 00:16:39,763
and you have to be vigilant about it.

358
00:16:43,550 --> 00:16:45,470
Eons ago, I was working on a project,

359
00:16:46,771 --> 00:16:50,232
and the producer on that project realized

360
00:16:50,312 --> 00:16:53,673
that there weren't enough touch points with the team

361
00:16:54,633 --> 00:16:56,093
and wanted to improve processes,

362
00:16:56,153 --> 00:16:57,254
wanted to do things differently

363
00:16:57,574 --> 00:16:59,454
from how this particular studio I was working at

364
00:16:59,814 --> 00:17:00,855
was doing things at the time.

365
00:17:01,995 --> 00:17:05,556
So that person wanted to institute mid-mortems,

366
00:17:06,096 --> 00:17:06,756
very reasonable,

367
00:17:08,377 --> 00:17:09,917
told the leads that...

368
00:17:10,772 --> 00:17:13,875
Now we were going to have updates regularly.

369
00:17:13,895 --> 00:17:16,538
And these were going to be built around

370
00:17:18,080 --> 00:17:19,181
essentially sprints.

371
00:17:19,981 --> 00:17:21,082
We didn't call them sprints.

372
00:17:21,563 --> 00:17:23,485
We knew that it was time to crunch a little bit.

373
00:17:24,005 --> 00:17:25,787
And we didn't want to use the word crunch.

374
00:17:27,229 --> 00:17:30,011
And we came up with a different word.

375
00:17:31,313 --> 00:17:32,574
I'm saying we generously.

376
00:17:33,194 --> 00:17:34,895
But a different word was used.

377
00:17:35,715 --> 00:17:37,015
And that word was surge.

378
00:17:37,055 --> 00:17:38,136
So we're going to surge ahead.

379
00:17:39,016 --> 00:17:41,577
This period of time, we're going to surge ahead.

380
00:17:41,597 --> 00:17:43,217
And then at the end of this surge,

381
00:17:43,417 --> 00:17:45,018
we're going to get together and talk about how it went.

382
00:17:46,639 --> 00:17:47,619
And then we're going to improve.

383
00:17:48,779 --> 00:17:51,900
So at the end of the surge, people have been crunching a bit.

384
00:17:52,657 --> 00:17:54,358
They had some goals that they'd started with.

385
00:17:54,959 --> 00:17:55,699
They got together.

386
00:17:56,259 --> 00:17:58,121
The whole team, the leads had been tasked

387
00:17:58,201 --> 00:18:00,722
with gathering up information from their team members

388
00:18:01,022 --> 00:18:01,783
about how things went.

389
00:18:02,223 --> 00:18:04,965
They got together, big room like this,

390
00:18:06,206 --> 00:18:07,566
and the leads came up one by one,

391
00:18:08,707 --> 00:18:12,349
and they wrote on a board what their top items were,

392
00:18:13,630 --> 00:18:15,952
and they all agreed on what the number one thing

393
00:18:15,992 --> 00:18:17,473
was that they could fix for the next time.

394
00:18:17,893 --> 00:18:18,433
Well, guess what?

395
00:18:19,594 --> 00:18:21,755
First one, number one thing, communication.

396
00:18:23,235 --> 00:18:24,195
Big letters on the board.

397
00:18:25,296 --> 00:18:26,336
Cool, we'll fix it.

398
00:18:27,817 --> 00:18:28,317
It went away.

399
00:18:29,518 --> 00:18:30,178
Another surge.

400
00:18:31,159 --> 00:18:33,680
Took goals from that first one, went into the next one,

401
00:18:34,441 --> 00:18:36,982
had that next AAR.

402
00:18:38,763 --> 00:18:39,343
Same thing.

403
00:18:40,164 --> 00:18:40,964
Communication.

404
00:18:41,384 --> 00:18:41,945
Big letters.

405
00:18:42,325 --> 00:18:43,085
Number one thing.

406
00:18:45,326 --> 00:18:47,227
At this point, I was starting to worry a little bit, just

407
00:18:47,267 --> 00:18:49,889
that, you know, I don't know how the team's thinking about

408
00:18:49,929 --> 00:18:50,429
this, but.

409
00:18:51,574 --> 00:18:54,776
you know, let it go. See, see how that works out.

410
00:18:57,718 --> 00:18:59,519
At that point, I wasn't in the same role

411
00:18:59,539 --> 00:19:02,541
that I'm in now. Although, I did speak with

412
00:19:02,581 --> 00:19:04,302
that producer a bit about some concerns that I

413
00:19:04,322 --> 00:19:04,442
had.

414
00:19:05,442 --> 00:19:11,566
Third time. What do you suppose happened? Well, here's

415
00:19:11,626 --> 00:19:16,689
what. As the lead started coming up, that producer

416
00:19:16,729 --> 00:19:19,971
said, but this time you can't say communication.

417
00:19:22,492 --> 00:19:23,513
So the leads looked around and said,

418
00:19:24,354 --> 00:19:24,874
we're good.

419
00:19:25,855 --> 00:19:26,575
Everything's great.

420
00:19:27,896 --> 00:19:28,477
Let's go back.

421
00:19:28,817 --> 00:19:30,358
That project shut down two weeks later.

422
00:19:33,040 --> 00:19:35,682
Communication's hard, and if you don't do something

423
00:19:35,762 --> 00:19:38,524
about it, you're gonna fail.

424
00:19:41,286 --> 00:19:42,727
And this is how we felt.

425
00:19:45,870 --> 00:19:46,830
So you can't ignore it.

426
00:19:49,893 --> 00:19:50,953
Here's a good best practice.

427
00:19:53,057 --> 00:19:54,799
By the way, I tend to like to bounce around a bit.

428
00:19:56,140 --> 00:19:59,863
So, for those of you who were in the talk I did last year,

429
00:20:00,624 --> 00:20:02,045
thank you for coming back this year.

430
00:20:03,246 --> 00:20:05,408
And for those who weren't, I'm just letting you know ahead of time,

431
00:20:05,428 --> 00:20:07,069
I like to move around a bit.

432
00:20:07,670 --> 00:20:10,372
So, saying I don't know is a best practice. I love that.

433
00:20:10,512 --> 00:20:13,635
This is how I'm looking for, when I look for new producers to work with.

434
00:20:14,475 --> 00:20:16,717
And I listen for how much experience people have

435
00:20:17,237 --> 00:20:17,938
when they say, I don't know,

436
00:20:17,978 --> 00:20:19,679
because I say, I don't know all the time.

437
00:20:19,859 --> 00:20:22,661
You can't possibly, this industry's moving so fast,

438
00:20:22,701 --> 00:20:24,763
and the things that we do are so complex.

439
00:20:24,803 --> 00:20:26,164
You have to say, I don't know sometimes.

440
00:20:27,545 --> 00:20:29,466
I don't know why anyone would try to fool us

441
00:20:29,526 --> 00:20:30,507
by saying that they do know

442
00:20:30,547 --> 00:20:32,348
or by indicating they know more than they do.

443
00:20:32,749 --> 00:20:34,830
But this is also how you gather up information

444
00:20:34,850 --> 00:20:38,733
to improve and to schedule and to work with your team.

445
00:20:38,793 --> 00:20:39,393
So look for that.

446
00:20:39,413 --> 00:20:41,355
You should value those simple words.

447
00:20:45,531 --> 00:20:47,152
Especially so we can avoid a death march.

448
00:20:49,634 --> 00:20:51,455
You guys recognize this graph? It's pretty well-known.

449
00:20:51,475 --> 00:20:54,237
Okay. Well,

450
00:20:56,498 --> 00:20:59,320
this is considered to be, at least Tufte,

451
00:20:59,400 --> 00:21:02,262
who, whose opinion I, I trust,

452
00:21:03,422 --> 00:21:05,904
says this is probably the best infographic ever made

453
00:21:07,005 --> 00:21:07,885
by Charles Menard.

454
00:21:10,393 --> 00:21:14,776
And this is an infographic about Napoleon's army's march

455
00:21:15,976 --> 00:21:17,437
into Russia, into Moscow.

456
00:21:18,918 --> 00:21:22,700
And what you see is the line that starts out

457
00:21:22,780 --> 00:21:27,003
quite broad on top and gets progressively narrower

458
00:21:27,103 --> 00:21:28,924
to the right as it approaches Moscow

459
00:21:29,484 --> 00:21:34,507
is the number of troops still in Napoleon's campaign.

460
00:21:35,328 --> 00:21:37,509
And then that black line on the way back

461
00:21:37,729 --> 00:21:39,610
is the continued death march home.

462
00:21:41,383 --> 00:21:45,584
And the graphics that you see here are about distance.

463
00:21:45,744 --> 00:21:46,664
They're about temperature.

464
00:21:46,684 --> 00:21:48,485
You can see temperature charted in the bottom.

465
00:21:50,066 --> 00:21:52,746
They're about latitude and longitude.

466
00:21:55,007 --> 00:21:56,447
And they tell a pretty stark story.

467
00:21:58,268 --> 00:22:04,230
Well, if Napoleon knew in advance that this is what the

468
00:22:04,290 --> 00:22:07,931
outcome would be, would he have still engaged his troops?

469
00:22:08,051 --> 00:22:08,431
I don't know.

470
00:22:08,771 --> 00:22:09,912
If he thought he'd won, maybe.

471
00:22:10,622 --> 00:22:11,143
Hard to say.

472
00:22:12,984 --> 00:22:17,488
This cost him his future in France

473
00:22:17,508 --> 00:22:19,870
to become the great emperor that he was looking to be.

474
00:22:21,752 --> 00:22:23,073
And as an infographic,

475
00:22:24,033 --> 00:22:25,535
it's very interesting.

476
00:22:26,816 --> 00:22:29,218
I want to make the point that, as producers,

477
00:22:29,678 --> 00:22:32,160
we use graphs all the time

478
00:22:32,861 --> 00:22:33,762
to communicate things.

479
00:22:34,651 --> 00:22:42,200
We use Gantt charts and burndowns and build fancy things in Excel to show the relationship.

480
00:22:42,220 --> 00:22:44,883
You know, we try to break things down to make them as simple as we can be.

481
00:22:45,944 --> 00:22:50,589
I think we probably still haven't gotten quite as elegant as what we see here,

482
00:22:51,069 --> 00:22:52,871
but I'd encourage you to think about...

483
00:22:53,732 --> 00:22:58,254
breaking away from a rigid practice

484
00:22:58,754 --> 00:23:00,555
of how you display information,

485
00:23:00,595 --> 00:23:02,296
especially quantitative information,

486
00:23:02,756 --> 00:23:04,097
to the teams that you work with.

487
00:23:04,737 --> 00:23:06,698
They're looking for something that distills

488
00:23:06,738 --> 00:23:08,278
the essence of where the project is.

489
00:23:08,519 --> 00:23:10,399
That's all we really care about at any time

490
00:23:10,820 --> 00:23:13,061
is where is the project, where is it going to be,

491
00:23:13,321 --> 00:23:14,641
especially at the executive level.

492
00:23:15,021 --> 00:23:17,322
Is this project going to be worth more than it costs

493
00:23:17,482 --> 00:23:19,483
by whatever number the P&L says it should be?

494
00:23:21,749 --> 00:23:23,651
you can convey that in ways that

495
00:23:24,551 --> 00:23:25,992
show the attitude of your project

496
00:23:26,312 --> 00:23:27,954
and the quality of the game that you're making.

497
00:23:30,035 --> 00:23:32,597
So just think about ways that you can visualize that data

498
00:23:34,398 --> 00:23:37,541
that will really come across to the audience you have

499
00:23:38,081 --> 00:23:41,323
in a way that conveys the heart of what makes your game special.

500
00:23:46,107 --> 00:23:48,629
Discipline, organization, and maturity are not things

501
00:23:48,669 --> 00:23:50,271
that we always found in the game industry.

502
00:23:50,751 --> 00:23:53,013
But I think we're doing a lot better job of that now,

503
00:23:53,233 --> 00:23:56,736
broadly, as game developers have gotten

504
00:23:57,176 --> 00:23:58,878
really experienced and mature over the years.

505
00:23:59,338 --> 00:24:01,880
And we should value the wisdom of those that have been around.

506
00:24:02,220 --> 00:24:04,042
But discipline is hard.

507
00:24:05,183 --> 00:24:06,664
Organization can be hard,

508
00:24:07,124 --> 00:24:11,688
especially for it to not feel overly bureaucratic,

509
00:24:11,748 --> 00:24:13,410
an environment that's looking for creativity.

510
00:24:14,150 --> 00:24:14,751
And maturity.

511
00:24:15,706 --> 00:24:18,227
I don't know much to say about maturity other than we value it.

512
00:24:23,930 --> 00:24:24,790
In this postmortem,

513
00:24:26,851 --> 00:24:29,632
this was a good game that came out last year,

514
00:24:29,672 --> 00:24:30,312
Lords of the Fallen.

515
00:24:32,693 --> 00:24:33,934
This team looks back and thinks,

516
00:24:34,254 --> 00:24:35,815
we're not really sure how we made that game,

517
00:24:37,115 --> 00:24:38,736
given the problems we had going into it.

518
00:24:41,250 --> 00:24:43,771
And they make the point that something they were really looking for,

519
00:24:44,491 --> 00:24:45,731
when they realized they needed it,

520
00:24:46,671 --> 00:24:47,512
was a person.

521
00:24:47,532 --> 00:24:48,912
They were looking for a person

522
00:24:50,052 --> 00:24:51,753
to come in and ask the tough questions

523
00:24:52,733 --> 00:24:54,993
and make the production decisions that needed to be made

524
00:24:55,173 --> 00:24:56,334
because they as a team

525
00:24:57,234 --> 00:24:58,414
had a very difficult time

526
00:24:59,194 --> 00:25:00,574
pulling things out of the game,

527
00:25:01,375 --> 00:25:02,135
cutting things out.

528
00:25:04,515 --> 00:25:07,716
And this really caught my eye.

529
00:25:09,169 --> 00:25:14,291
I don't know what happens on a project to get to the point where the publisher is now

530
00:25:14,351 --> 00:25:17,013
coming in heavily and creative.

531
00:25:17,053 --> 00:25:21,995
They talk about the publisher at this point is actually doing level design, is doing map

532
00:25:22,015 --> 00:25:22,975
design and mission design.

533
00:25:25,777 --> 00:25:32,280
Something's happened in that crazy, chaotic environment where those tough questions aren't

534
00:25:32,320 --> 00:25:35,781
being asked, where the publisher now is having a creative role.

535
00:25:36,823 --> 00:25:39,246
certainly beyond whatever they thought they were signing up to in the beginning,

536
00:25:40,066 --> 00:25:41,928
and not enough communication has been happening.

537
00:25:43,570 --> 00:25:45,392
So somebody needed to come in and create some structure.

538
00:25:45,953 --> 00:25:50,998
And every studio environment, you need structure to give people the trust

539
00:25:51,278 --> 00:25:54,902
that things are going the way they should, to be making a good game.

540
00:25:55,242 --> 00:25:58,426
So I say basically they had not thought about establishing those guidelines for communication.

541
00:25:59,562 --> 00:26:01,904
And once they got the right person in the environment,

542
00:26:02,265 --> 00:26:04,247
that stopped crazy communication happening

543
00:26:04,627 --> 00:26:05,989
between the publisher and the developer

544
00:26:06,389 --> 00:26:07,851
and employing channel people.

545
00:26:08,211 --> 00:26:13,877
Now, every good organization,

546
00:26:14,177 --> 00:26:16,860
it's clear who has responsibility and authority for what.

547
00:26:17,881 --> 00:26:18,021
So...

548
00:26:19,099 --> 00:26:25,403
you should know who in your team is talking with the person on the other side,

549
00:26:25,883 --> 00:26:28,004
if you're working in that developer-publisher relationship.

550
00:26:28,084 --> 00:26:29,605
If you're self-funded, cool.

551
00:26:29,905 --> 00:26:33,187
At least then, though, you should be understanding more about who the customer is,

552
00:26:34,068 --> 00:26:35,108
where are you going to market,

553
00:26:35,629 --> 00:26:40,011
if you're having that sort of direct interaction with customers.

554
00:26:41,672 --> 00:26:44,173
And in that sense, I mean customers who are buying the game.

555
00:26:46,515 --> 00:26:49,456
You have to really understand the structure though, and if you don't,

556
00:26:49,876 --> 00:26:51,517
go make sure that you do.

557
00:26:51,577 --> 00:26:54,219
Start asking hard questions about who's responsible for

558
00:26:54,579 --> 00:26:58,281
which parts of communication with finance, with publishing, with marketing.

559
00:27:01,242 --> 00:27:02,923
But information's not going to move by itself.

560
00:27:02,963 --> 00:27:03,743
You have to do things.

561
00:27:06,340 --> 00:27:08,641
The problem that I've seen time and time again

562
00:27:08,661 --> 00:27:10,562
is simply people not getting out of their chairs.

563
00:27:10,922 --> 00:27:14,023
So you can lead by example to get up, walk around.

564
00:27:14,063 --> 00:27:15,324
As I said, I do that all the time.

565
00:27:15,784 --> 00:27:17,145
Just by you getting up and walking around,

566
00:27:17,205 --> 00:27:19,666
you can show you don't have to be stuck in your chair all day.

567
00:27:19,706 --> 00:27:21,787
But also, some people need some prodding.

568
00:27:22,127 --> 00:27:24,168
You want to do that if the information that they have

569
00:27:24,228 --> 00:27:25,009
is vital to others.

570
00:27:26,269 --> 00:27:29,491
For example, there may be a rendering programmer,

571
00:27:29,511 --> 00:27:30,431
a graphics programmer,

572
00:27:31,012 --> 00:27:32,973
who's working on things that are really important.

573
00:27:33,953 --> 00:27:36,876
to the technical artists and artists and, you know,

574
00:27:37,216 --> 00:27:40,218
level designers and your lighting artists on the team.

575
00:27:41,179 --> 00:27:43,801
And for some reason, that communication hasn't happened

576
00:27:43,841 --> 00:27:45,683
in a way where they know what to expect

577
00:27:46,023 --> 00:27:47,204
at their next big milestone.

578
00:27:48,345 --> 00:27:49,466
Something has to happen,

579
00:27:49,666 --> 00:27:51,127
and you have to be the one to do it

580
00:27:52,868 --> 00:27:54,270
to cause that communication to happen

581
00:27:54,290 --> 00:27:56,031
for those specifications to be written down.

582
00:27:56,832 --> 00:27:58,313
But there are a lot of kinds of, you know,

583
00:27:58,793 --> 00:27:59,714
different people are different.

584
00:28:01,435 --> 00:28:02,916
And they get into this rut of.

585
00:28:03,463 --> 00:28:04,624
not sharing information.

586
00:28:05,204 --> 00:28:08,125
So you have to get it from people into a format that's usable.

587
00:28:10,305 --> 00:28:10,726
And it's hard.

588
00:28:13,006 --> 00:28:15,307
But reminding people what they're doing is awesome really helps.

589
00:28:16,007 --> 00:28:17,908
That encourages them to get up and walk.

590
00:28:18,168 --> 00:28:20,969
It encourages the kind of specificity that you need

591
00:28:21,609 --> 00:28:23,809
to move forward, because they get passionate,

592
00:28:23,829 --> 00:28:24,910
they feel good about what they're doing,

593
00:28:24,970 --> 00:28:26,670
and then you give them a structure in which to work.

594
00:28:27,889 --> 00:28:30,150
And you can funnel that passion into something.

595
00:28:30,210 --> 00:28:33,090
Those who are checked out are not actually going to provide

596
00:28:33,110 --> 00:28:36,271
you the kind of data that you need, the kind of specificity,

597
00:28:37,591 --> 00:28:41,572
for others to understand what they should be doing, or how

598
00:28:41,592 --> 00:28:44,092
to use this tool that's being developed, or this tech that's

599
00:28:44,112 --> 00:28:48,513
being developed, or when does level art come into what your

600
00:28:48,533 --> 00:28:49,253
mappers are doing.

601
00:28:50,533 --> 00:28:52,234
Those who feel good about what they're doing are going to be

602
00:28:52,294 --> 00:28:53,614
more vocal in a positive way.

603
00:28:56,634 --> 00:28:57,635
You guys play Shadows of Mordor?

604
00:28:58,910 --> 00:28:59,430
It's a good game.

605
00:29:01,011 --> 00:29:02,432
Well, in their post-mortem,

606
00:29:05,653 --> 00:29:07,434
it's funny, the thing everybody talks about with that game

607
00:29:07,454 --> 00:29:08,315
is the nemesis system.

608
00:29:09,175 --> 00:29:11,477
And they talk about how they didn't do a very good job

609
00:29:11,517 --> 00:29:12,877
of communicating the promise of it,

610
00:29:13,618 --> 00:29:14,779
internally or externally,

611
00:29:15,499 --> 00:29:16,620
for a long time.

612
00:29:19,261 --> 00:29:20,502
And it created them some issues

613
00:29:21,782 --> 00:29:24,404
as far as spending extra cycles on things

614
00:29:24,884 --> 00:29:26,865
that they could have cut out much sooner than they did.

615
00:29:29,915 --> 00:29:31,716
And they needed somebody in that team,

616
00:29:32,837 --> 00:29:34,118
and you as a producer can do this,

617
00:29:35,118 --> 00:29:38,100
to evangelize a system like that,

618
00:29:38,140 --> 00:29:39,761
the thing that's going to make your game special,

619
00:29:40,361 --> 00:29:43,843
whatever it is, to promote that all around.

620
00:29:45,244 --> 00:29:46,724
When I was at Origin, we would do that.

621
00:29:46,764 --> 00:29:48,005
We would make posters of things,

622
00:29:48,045 --> 00:29:49,886
and I saw other teams inside EA do it,

623
00:29:49,926 --> 00:29:52,988
to really promote what they were doing inside of the system,

624
00:29:53,408 --> 00:29:56,530
to really gain buzz and favor for their projects.

625
00:29:58,164 --> 00:30:00,965
And that's a good thing, to let people know what is special about what you're doing.

626
00:30:01,025 --> 00:30:05,066
And then to connect the people who are working on that special thing with others.

627
00:30:06,247 --> 00:30:08,988
It fuels the passion for making it.

628
00:30:13,289 --> 00:30:14,429
This is a post-mortem from 1999.

629
00:30:14,589 --> 00:30:18,731
It's one of the ones that I used a lot when I was teaching at the Guild Hall still.

630
00:30:22,619 --> 00:30:25,840
Ken Birdwell here talks about the cabal process,

631
00:30:26,060 --> 00:30:28,021
how that evolved on the first Half-Life.

632
00:30:29,821 --> 00:30:31,682
And what it evolved in response to.

633
00:30:32,602 --> 00:30:34,703
And now we call, you know, this is pretty common now.

634
00:30:34,723 --> 00:30:37,464
Strike teams, tiger teams, some people just call them cabals.

635
00:30:37,484 --> 00:30:41,265
We just, we like to group people around features,

636
00:30:42,145 --> 00:30:44,286
things where you can have efficient communication.

637
00:30:46,170 --> 00:30:47,951
But there's a couple of interesting points here

638
00:30:48,351 --> 00:30:49,311
that I still like to look to.

639
00:30:49,952 --> 00:30:51,592
So one of them is, during that process,

640
00:30:51,952 --> 00:30:54,573
they realized that even though level designers

641
00:30:54,633 --> 00:30:55,873
knew about some feature that was made,

642
00:30:55,953 --> 00:30:58,474
in this case, he's talking about a Beam tech

643
00:30:58,554 --> 00:30:59,955
that, um, Code had worked on.

644
00:31:00,615 --> 00:31:02,035
Nobody was using it. They didn't know what it was for.

645
00:31:02,416 --> 00:31:04,356
Hadn't been communicated to them what was special about it.

646
00:31:04,556 --> 00:31:06,057
All those points that were just made,

647
00:31:06,477 --> 00:31:07,217
they weren't doing that.

648
00:31:09,458 --> 00:31:10,578
And their solution was,

649
00:31:10,878 --> 00:31:11,979
well, the Beam tech's made.

650
00:31:12,599 --> 00:31:13,719
It'd be cool if it was used.

651
00:31:14,820 --> 00:31:14,980
So...

652
00:31:15,843 --> 00:31:18,704
The solution is, tell them they need to integrate it,

653
00:31:19,725 --> 00:31:20,806
train them on how to do it,

654
00:31:21,286 --> 00:31:23,067
and then follow through to make sure they really do it.

655
00:31:25,308 --> 00:31:26,509
Now, smart and creative people

656
00:31:26,909 --> 00:31:28,950
don't usually like to be told they have to do a thing

657
00:31:29,150 --> 00:31:30,991
unless they think, especially if you're a level designer

658
00:31:31,011 --> 00:31:31,852
in this kind of environment.

659
00:31:32,352 --> 00:31:34,833
You want to know, I mean, you basically own that level,

660
00:31:35,054 --> 00:31:36,414
right, as that LD.

661
00:31:36,955 --> 00:31:39,556
So you want it to be cool enough where you want to use it.

662
00:31:39,856 --> 00:31:41,297
Not, not that you're told you have to.

663
00:31:41,497 --> 00:31:43,678
But sometimes as producers we have to ride that line.

664
00:31:48,476 --> 00:31:52,418
So you have to make sure you know, and that everybody else knows,

665
00:31:53,399 --> 00:31:55,841
who the customer and the provider of everything that's being done are.

666
00:31:56,861 --> 00:32:01,424
And in your tasks, if you use Jira, let's say, or Hansoft, or whatever you're using,

667
00:32:01,844 --> 00:32:04,586
make sure that it's really clear who's responsible,

668
00:32:04,946 --> 00:32:07,168
who had the vision for a thing, who...

669
00:32:08,334 --> 00:32:11,275
should the implementer go to for more information.

670
00:32:12,156 --> 00:32:14,317
And then if you're in a system like ours,

671
00:32:14,337 --> 00:32:16,839
a lot of times what we do is we essentially hand off

672
00:32:17,379 --> 00:32:19,921
ownership to a person who says they really get the intent.

673
00:32:20,421 --> 00:32:22,082
But for questions, they know how to follow up.

674
00:32:23,363 --> 00:32:25,885
In the past, on Borderlands 1, for example, we saw this.

675
00:32:26,866 --> 00:32:28,186
Some feature request would go in.

676
00:32:29,187 --> 00:32:31,729
It would sit in our task management system for a while.

677
00:32:32,309 --> 00:32:33,210
Wouldn't get a lot of love.

678
00:32:34,129 --> 00:32:36,630
Eventually it'd get picked up, and then it'd be implemented

679
00:32:37,070 --> 00:32:38,511
in essentially a vacuum.

680
00:32:39,812 --> 00:32:41,893
Until we realized in a playable build,

681
00:32:42,133 --> 00:32:44,254
maybe a month later, what had gone wrong

682
00:32:44,314 --> 00:32:46,215
and seeing if we could catch up to fix it.

683
00:32:46,755 --> 00:32:48,016
Well, that's not a best practice,

684
00:32:48,396 --> 00:32:49,996
so I hope that you're doing something better than that.

685
00:32:51,737 --> 00:32:52,878
And one of the things that we do now

686
00:32:52,958 --> 00:32:54,358
is we always make sure we know

687
00:32:54,919 --> 00:32:56,519
who the customer is for a feature.

688
00:32:56,579 --> 00:32:58,660
Now, in this case, I mean customer on the team.

689
00:32:59,601 --> 00:33:01,622
Who's the person on the team that needs a thing?

690
00:33:02,576 --> 00:33:05,458
And out of that, also we developed, we, we built our,

691
00:33:06,238 --> 00:33:07,399
our tools programming team,

692
00:33:09,700 --> 00:33:11,281
who always know who their customers are

693
00:33:12,041 --> 00:33:13,962
around, around the studio.

694
00:33:20,365 --> 00:33:23,367
We see, we don't see this as often anymore,

695
00:33:24,227 --> 00:33:26,188
but, man, it's always frustrating.

696
00:33:26,208 --> 00:33:27,949
You, you must have been in a meeting at some point

697
00:33:28,290 --> 00:33:30,631
where you realized the thing that everybody's arguing about

698
00:33:30,671 --> 00:33:31,972
is something nobody really knows about.

699
00:33:34,097 --> 00:33:35,538
And then you start making calls, hopefully.

700
00:33:35,738 --> 00:33:37,579
Or you do something, or you postpone that meeting.

701
00:33:37,619 --> 00:33:39,861
But if it's a decision that has to be made right then,

702
00:33:40,642 --> 00:33:42,523
you shouldn't probably have gotten to that point.

703
00:33:43,364 --> 00:33:47,027
You should be more careful about how your meetings are structured

704
00:33:47,747 --> 00:33:51,630
so that prior discussion happens before you get to that point.

705
00:33:51,970 --> 00:33:53,051
So think about actually a...

706
00:33:54,345 --> 00:33:57,486
a plan for your meetings that stages them in a way

707
00:33:57,927 --> 00:33:59,907
that the right information gets to the point where

708
00:33:59,927 --> 00:34:02,288
that eventual decision-making meeting happens.

709
00:34:02,928 --> 00:34:05,729
Or allow decisions to be made in those meetings

710
00:34:05,789 --> 00:34:07,630
by the people who are actually doing the work.

711
00:34:08,130 --> 00:34:09,510
You have to decide, but you don't want to get

712
00:34:09,810 --> 00:34:10,391
to this point.

713
00:34:11,131 --> 00:34:13,992
We still see that, but not as often, like I said.

714
00:34:18,753 --> 00:34:20,634
So again, communication's hard.

715
00:34:22,821 --> 00:34:25,704
Some of the harder things that we have to do in production

716
00:34:28,207 --> 00:34:28,828
are these three.

717
00:34:30,169 --> 00:34:33,093
Hiring. Hiring is one of the most difficult and important things

718
00:34:33,133 --> 00:34:34,354
that we can do and get it right.

719
00:34:34,675 --> 00:34:36,797
And it costs us so much when we get it wrong.

720
00:34:37,358 --> 00:34:38,859
And it costs us so much just to do it.

721
00:34:42,413 --> 00:34:44,615
Right now we're going through thousands of resumes

722
00:34:44,755 --> 00:34:47,137
in the studio, where I am, at Gearbox.

723
00:34:47,417 --> 00:34:49,438
And it's a huge process.

724
00:34:50,619 --> 00:34:51,560
And all of you know this, too.

725
00:34:51,660 --> 00:34:52,861
If you've hired anybody, you know how,

726
00:34:53,622 --> 00:34:55,483
unless it was your buddy, you know,

727
00:34:55,783 --> 00:34:57,485
which, then at least you have trust for your buddy.

728
00:34:58,005 --> 00:35:00,607
But it's hard when you get it wrong.

729
00:35:01,107 --> 00:35:02,889
Assessing, assessing a situation

730
00:35:03,289 --> 00:35:04,910
when you have two different points of view

731
00:35:06,091 --> 00:35:07,593
is enormously difficult.

732
00:35:08,733 --> 00:35:11,055
There are tactics that you can employ.

733
00:35:12,486 --> 00:35:15,767
when talking to different, people with different points of view.

734
00:35:16,007 --> 00:35:18,348
And sometimes one of those people isn't wrong.

735
00:35:20,149 --> 00:35:21,070
Sometimes they're both right.

736
00:35:22,070 --> 00:35:23,070
Or they could both be wrong.

737
00:35:23,351 --> 00:35:24,771
But you have to be able to assess that for yourself.

738
00:35:24,811 --> 00:35:26,892
And if you don't have the technical or domain expertise,

739
00:35:27,172 --> 00:35:29,573
and it's not a technical issue, and you're trying to solve it,

740
00:35:30,114 --> 00:35:31,254
either you're making a mistake,

741
00:35:32,215 --> 00:35:34,636
or you just need to bring others into that discussion to help you,

742
00:35:36,056 --> 00:35:38,718
or you're just really comfortable kind of playing it from the hip,

743
00:35:39,358 --> 00:35:40,258
and maybe you'll get it right.

744
00:35:40,728 --> 00:35:43,509
maybe it doesn't matter. Maybe you just need to make a decision so you can move on.

745
00:35:44,409 --> 00:35:46,530
Which is sometimes the best answer.

746
00:35:46,930 --> 00:35:50,111
Sometimes you just need to make a decision so that you can move forward.

747
00:35:50,491 --> 00:35:52,331
But hopefully you're being diligent about that.

748
00:35:52,931 --> 00:35:56,732
Because if you make a technical decision on a topic you don't really know about,

749
00:35:57,012 --> 00:35:58,892
but maybe you think you do, and you're kind of fudging it,

750
00:36:00,353 --> 00:36:02,113
the people that you're talking to know you don't know it.

751
00:36:03,493 --> 00:36:03,914
So watch out.

752
00:36:04,694 --> 00:36:05,714
And resolving disputes.

753
00:36:06,194 --> 00:36:08,735
Similar topic, but in this one, a little more aggressive.

754
00:36:11,732 --> 00:36:13,373
Now, on the topic of hiring,

755
00:36:16,855 --> 00:36:19,636
have you heard of behavioral descriptive questioning before?

756
00:36:19,656 --> 00:36:21,497
A few of us, a couple.

757
00:36:21,917 --> 00:36:23,598
It's something that's really good for you to understand.

758
00:36:24,298 --> 00:36:25,019
It's really simple.

759
00:36:25,459 --> 00:36:26,479
It's no magic to it.

760
00:36:26,799 --> 00:36:28,640
It's just asking people questions

761
00:36:28,920 --> 00:36:31,262
that gets to the specifics of what they actually did.

762
00:36:32,722 --> 00:36:35,524
New hiring managers or people who are involved in hiring

763
00:36:37,465 --> 00:36:39,666
sometimes just make assumptions.

764
00:36:40,662 --> 00:36:44,584
Maybe not so much that the person is, you know,

765
00:36:46,184 --> 00:36:48,385
always has actually done the things that they're talking about,

766
00:36:48,765 --> 00:36:52,046
but more, maybe they're, maybe the person that you're talking to,

767
00:36:52,146 --> 00:36:55,267
that, that candidate, really means well.

