1027
00:48:53,143 --> 00:48:55,004
And sort of calling out some of the comments

1028
00:48:55,064 --> 00:48:57,545
about why people thought that tool

1029
00:48:57,585 --> 00:49:01,047
or that approach that person was using wasn't the best.

1030
00:49:01,987 --> 00:49:04,528
And then I saw this kind of back and forth,

1031
00:49:04,568 --> 00:49:06,569
very thinly veiled passive-aggressive

1032
00:49:07,209 --> 00:49:10,171
back and forth happen that we had to put the kibosh on.

1033
00:49:11,131 --> 00:49:12,552
And we did.

1034
00:49:12,832 --> 00:49:15,413
And then it's funny, once we talked to the people involved,

1035
00:49:16,413 --> 00:49:17,874
you know, whether or not they really knew

1036
00:49:17,934 --> 00:49:18,714
what they were doing,

1037
00:49:18,954 --> 00:49:20,195
they kind of expressed they didn't.

1038
00:49:20,635 --> 00:49:22,356
They were just kind of trying to get their point across.

1039
00:49:22,696 --> 00:49:24,396
And you as a producer have to be the adult there.

1040
00:49:25,957 --> 00:49:26,657
No name-calling.

1041
00:49:27,898 --> 00:49:29,018
And at the same time, though...

1042
00:49:30,088 --> 00:49:33,190
If you're hearing those kind of things, so and so is stupid.

1043
00:49:33,891 --> 00:49:36,672
Now, that's different from this thing that we're doing is stupid, right?

1044
00:49:38,453 --> 00:49:43,496
Don't tolerate low performance, because if you let people stay around your environment

1045
00:49:43,576 --> 00:49:47,018
who are low performers, that's gonna tank the performance and the morale of everybody

1046
00:49:47,078 --> 00:49:47,599
else, right?

1047
00:49:48,099 --> 00:49:49,800
So if you have a low performer, you have to get rid of them.

1048
00:49:51,541 --> 00:49:55,263
Don't let them just sit there in the environment and get kicked around a lot.

1049
00:49:55,483 --> 00:49:56,023
They have to go.

1050
00:49:57,084 --> 00:49:58,205
You can't have saccharine cows there.

1051
00:49:59,169 --> 00:50:00,850
And you have to get rid of bad processes.

1052
00:50:00,890 --> 00:50:02,631
So if somebody says this process is stupid,

1053
00:50:03,031 --> 00:50:04,772
well, talk it through.

1054
00:50:05,153 --> 00:50:06,693
It's possible the process is stupid.

1055
00:50:08,955 --> 00:50:12,056
But at the same time, unless you've really understood

1056
00:50:12,697 --> 00:50:13,857
where that person's coming from,

1057
00:50:14,538 --> 00:50:15,759
you can't assess.

1058
00:50:16,059 --> 00:50:17,740
Just same as what we were saying before.

1059
00:50:18,000 --> 00:50:20,081
If you don't have the technical expertise and domain,

1060
00:50:20,101 --> 00:50:21,802
you can't really know if you don't get more help.

1061
00:50:27,225 --> 00:50:27,385
So...

1062
00:50:29,263 --> 00:50:30,604
Going back to communications hard.

1063
00:50:33,526 --> 00:50:36,749
I was talking to a project producer a few years ago

1064
00:50:37,490 --> 00:50:41,353
who had a kind of a monumental set of tasks on top of them.

1065
00:50:41,393 --> 00:50:44,595
They had a really hard job to do

1066
00:50:44,635 --> 00:50:46,317
based on the nature of what they were trying to ship.

1067
00:50:47,678 --> 00:50:49,820
And then they had more and more things heaped on top of them.

1068
00:50:51,421 --> 00:50:54,063
And so that person kind of delegated a bit,

1069
00:50:54,263 --> 00:50:55,084
a very small amount,

1070
00:50:55,925 --> 00:50:57,906
some production responsibility of some of those other things.

1071
00:50:59,352 --> 00:51:02,813
And that producer came to me and just completely befuddled,

1072
00:51:03,494 --> 00:51:05,495
totally befuddled, said this.

1073
00:51:05,735 --> 00:51:07,195
They had the same information as me.

1074
00:51:07,535 --> 00:51:09,556
How could they possibly have come to a different conclusion?

1075
00:51:09,797 --> 00:51:10,737
Something's wrong with that person.

1076
00:51:10,757 --> 00:51:11,297
You should fire them.

1077
00:51:15,559 --> 00:51:18,701
After sitting down with the person in question and this

1078
00:51:18,741 --> 00:51:22,582
producer, realized all the decisions that had been made

1079
00:51:22,783 --> 00:51:25,724
were great decisions for these things that had been

1080
00:51:25,764 --> 00:51:26,164
delegated.

1081
00:51:26,524 --> 00:51:27,505
They were actually great decisions.

1082
00:51:27,785 --> 00:51:28,665
They made the product better.

1083
00:51:29,878 --> 00:51:32,921
but there had been a failure to communicate and set expectations

1084
00:51:33,722 --> 00:51:34,783
as changes happened.

1085
00:51:35,643 --> 00:51:37,405
Kind of like staying on top of that rolling wave.

1086
00:51:38,086 --> 00:51:42,170
And so, because the end result of those decisions was so different

1087
00:51:42,470 --> 00:51:45,112
from what the producer thought was going to happen in the beginning,

1088
00:51:45,733 --> 00:51:47,174
all they could see what the result was

1089
00:51:47,194 --> 00:51:49,837
and immediately see it as all bad.

1090
00:51:51,258 --> 00:51:53,140
And it took a long time, actually.

1091
00:51:54,404 --> 00:51:56,346
In this case, I mean, every hour is expensive.

1092
00:51:56,386 --> 00:51:58,547
It took a couple of days to work it out

1093
00:51:58,687 --> 00:52:00,149
and see that actually it was okay.

1094
00:52:02,130 --> 00:52:03,631
But that communication goes both ways.

1095
00:52:03,671 --> 00:52:06,153
It's why it's important for you to communicate up well

1096
00:52:06,753 --> 00:52:09,075
to your leads and set those expectations

1097
00:52:09,375 --> 00:52:11,857
and do the same with the team that you're working with,

1098
00:52:12,177 --> 00:52:14,259
your peers, collaborators, and your teams.

1099
00:52:14,559 --> 00:52:16,521
You have to be constantly setting those expectations,

1100
00:52:16,861 --> 00:52:18,602
or people will see a thing that happens later

1101
00:52:18,622 --> 00:52:21,344
and react to it very differently

1102
00:52:21,384 --> 00:52:23,266
than if they understood the expectation up front.

1103
00:52:26,780 --> 00:52:31,702
Communication's hard. Some cats are going to sneak by you.

1104
00:52:31,722 --> 00:52:32,942
It's impossible to get them all.

1105
00:52:35,062 --> 00:52:38,363
You could be patient. You could learn about people more.

1106
00:52:38,803 --> 00:52:41,524
You can find out that you can do things to bring them to you.

1107
00:52:42,044 --> 00:52:46,865
Even the most belligerent people up front getting to know you.

1108
00:52:47,165 --> 00:52:49,806
Understanding not just your intent, because everybody can have good intent.

1109
00:52:50,206 --> 00:52:52,567
But if they see that you're trying hard and that you're learning,

1110
00:52:53,107 --> 00:52:54,427
and you're learning about what they do.

1111
00:52:55,629 --> 00:52:57,910
and that you appreciate and respect them,

1112
00:52:59,531 --> 00:53:03,353
and you don't allow yourself to fall into bad habits.

1113
00:53:03,433 --> 00:53:05,575
If you're really setting the standard,

1114
00:53:05,895 --> 00:53:06,835
people will flock to you.

1115
00:53:07,195 --> 00:53:08,976
They'll talk about you like,

1116
00:53:11,118 --> 00:53:11,298
well,

1117
00:53:12,238 --> 00:53:14,860
God, I was going to say the cat's meow,

1118
00:53:15,000 --> 00:53:17,201
but I can't help it.

1119
00:53:17,261 --> 00:53:18,021
Free association.

1120
00:53:21,083 --> 00:53:22,604
They will always want to work with you.

1121
00:53:23,024 --> 00:53:23,184
Okay.

1122
00:53:24,837 --> 00:53:25,597
Let them come to you.

1123
00:53:30,100 --> 00:53:33,262
Perfect communication, guys, is not possible. It's why,

1124
00:53:33,282 --> 00:53:36,204
in the description for the talk, I said, it's

1125
00:53:36,244 --> 00:53:38,225
hard, might as well give up now. OK.

1126
00:53:39,406 --> 00:53:42,568
And I'm giving us some hyperbole. It's, it isn't

1127
00:53:42,668 --> 00:53:44,909
possible to have perfect communication, because again, you only

1128
00:53:44,969 --> 00:53:47,731
control what you do. Right. So if you want

1129
00:53:48,191 --> 00:53:50,533
perfect, if you're always going to be frustrated because

1130
00:53:50,573 --> 00:53:52,754
things you say are going to be mistaken, all

1131
00:53:52,794 --> 00:53:54,295
you can do is improve your side of it.

1132
00:53:56,770 --> 00:53:58,730
You have to practice your communication skills.

1133
00:53:59,310 --> 00:54:02,131
The way that you break down tasks, what you learn,

1134
00:54:02,891 --> 00:54:06,552
the domains of the people around you, the wave of what's happening

1135
00:54:07,012 --> 00:54:08,252
in technology around you.

1136
00:54:09,092 --> 00:54:10,613
This industry is changing so fast.

1137
00:54:10,873 --> 00:54:12,053
You have to stay on top of it.

1138
00:54:14,493 --> 00:54:17,394
And I want to see you all, as you succeed, or not,

1139
00:54:17,434 --> 00:54:19,774
whatever's happening on your projects, keep learning.

1140
00:54:20,255 --> 00:54:22,215
Help us as a community learn.

1141
00:54:22,655 --> 00:54:23,575
Share what you've learned.

1142
00:54:24,318 --> 00:54:25,298
And write new postmortems.

1143
00:54:27,779 --> 00:54:28,679
And that's it.

1144
00:54:30,079 --> 00:54:30,379
Thank you.

1145
00:54:30,399 --> 00:54:40,662
applause

1146
00:54:40,682 --> 00:54:41,022
Thank you.

